{"title":"Machines for Freedom takes high-quality women’s ride gear off road","link":"https://bikerumor.com/2021/06/25/machines-for-freedom-versatile-off-road-collection/","date":1624625945000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><div><p><span>There’s nothing quite like slipping into a cycling kit that just fits perfectly. Aside from looking amazing, a combo of a properly fitting bib, jersey, and weather-specific accouterments bring an added boost of confidence and comfort that will help riders perform at their peak.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span>But in the mountain bike world, women’s apparel has tended to lag behind men’s offerings, whether in form, function, or style.</span></p><p><span><a href=\"https://www.machinesforfreedom.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Machines for Freedom</a> launched five years ago with the goal of addressing that exact issue by making cycling apparel for women that really works.</span></p><p><span>They offer dozens of items in unique styles and colors including bibs, pants, liners, jerseys and bras made specifically for women on two wheels.</span></p><p><span>This year, Machines has taken their mission into the mountain bike world with the brand-new Versatile Off Road Collection, a robust lineup of trail-ready clothing that’s ready to shred, from base garments to outerwear.</span></p><h2>Versatile Off Road Collection</h2><p><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection.jpeg\" alt=\"machines for freedom offroad collection\" width=\"1280\" height=\"563\" srcset=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection.jpeg 1280w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-297x131.jpeg 297w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-800x352.jpeg 800w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-120x53.jpeg 120w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-768x338.jpeg 768w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-696x306.jpeg 696w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-1068x470.jpeg 1068w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105818/machines-for-freedom-offroad-collection-955x420.jpeg 955w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb20 src ng ngcb20 srcset\"></p><p><span>The <a href=\"https://www.machinesforfreedom.com/collections/versatile-off-road\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Versatile Off Road Collection</a> brings a casual feel to biking apparel synonymous with off-road riding. Unlike skin-tight lycra bibs, speed suits, and jerseys, the Versatile Collection features loose-fitting outwear designed to feel great on or off the bike.</span></p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601.jpg\" alt=\"Machines for Freedom short storage\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" srcset=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601.jpg 1200w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-297x198.jpg 297w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-800x533.jpg 800w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-120x80.jpg 120w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-768x512.jpg 768w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-696x464.jpg 696w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-1068x712.jpg 1068w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085403/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_1601-630x420.jpg 630w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb20 src ng ngcb20 srcset\"></a></p><p><span>The lineup includes the headlining Key Trail Short, which comes in 5.5 or 11-inch inseam options, along with a high-rise design and stretchy fabric that is perfectly suited for carving up gravel, single track, or your daily commute.&nbsp;</span></p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611.jpg\" alt=\"Machines for Freedom pockets\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" srcset=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611.jpg 1200w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-297x198.jpg 297w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-800x533.jpg 800w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-120x80.jpg 120w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-768x512.jpg 768w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-696x464.jpg 696w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-1068x712.jpg 1068w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085358/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0611-630x420.jpg 630w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb20 src ng ngcb20 srcset\"></a></p><p><span>The collection also includes short and long sleeve technical and crew tees, and the Foundations Sports Bra and Liner Short.</span></p><p><span>The Liner Short is particularly appealing for riding that doesn’t really require the comprehensive padding a full bib would offer. Instead, the liner is a less-bulky alternative to a traditional chamois that still carries enough padding for a comfortable ride, along with a breathable mesh detailing on the legs and back for ventilation.</span></p><p><span>The bra brings all the ventilation and moisture-wicking performance you’d expect in cycling apparel in a comfortable package that is just as practical for use off the bike.&nbsp;</span></p><h2>The Mission</h2><p><span>Jennifer Kriske started Machines for Freedom in Malibu in 2014 after struggling with uncomfortable apparel and lack-luster </span><span>offerings, even from big-name cycling apparel companies.</span></p><p><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad.jpeg\" alt=\"Machines For Freedom apparel\" width=\"1150\" height=\"505\" srcset=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad.jpeg 1150w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-297x130.jpeg 297w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-800x351.jpeg 800w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-120x53.jpeg 120w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-768x337.jpeg 768w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-696x306.jpeg 696w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-1068x469.jpeg 1068w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/24105927/machines-for-freedom-offroad-956x420.jpeg 956w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1150px) 100vw, 1150px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb20 src ng ngcb20 srcset\"></p><p><span>“I honestly think that for a long time, clothing was an obstacle to women getting on a bike,” Kriske said. “Like, to feel self-conscious like that, that’s a powerful thing, and that’s a powerful demotivator for people.”</span></p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046.jpg\" alt=\"Machines for Freedom girl on bike climbing\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" srcset=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046.jpg 1200w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-297x198.jpg 297w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-800x533.jpg 800w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-120x80.jpg 120w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-768x512.jpg 768w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-696x464.jpg 696w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-1068x712.jpg 1068w, https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/25085353/2021_MachineForFreedom_MountainBikingCampaign_0046-630x420.jpg 630w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb20 src ng ngcb20 srcset\"></a></p><p><span>With the line of clothing <a href=\"https://www.machinesforfreedom.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Machines for Freedom</a> has created, she said she hopes to make women feel better, and perform better, every time they get on a bike.</span></p><p><span>“I think at our core, our product ethos is to help women feel amazing when they step out the door in a cycling kit,” she said. “We want to inspire confidence.”</span></p><p><a href=\"https://www.machinesforfreedom.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>machinesforfreedom.com</em></a></p></div></div>","author":"Mark Wilson","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"213540e2867736f82259c7737f9bf8ecb38d86366d0656efcbd326ffdfcae43b","category":"Cycling"}